// CORS 
    CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) is a browser security feature.

It controls which web applications (origins) are allowed to call your API.
  🔹 An origin = protocol + domain + port
Examples:
  https://example.com
  http://localhost:3000


Where is CORS used in ASP.NET Core?
    CORS is configured in two places:
      Services configuration (Program.cs)
      Middleware pipeline (app.UseCors())
    You can apply CORS:
      Globally (entire API)
      Per controller
      Per action

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

builder.Services.AddCors(options =>
{
    options.AddPolicy("AllowFrontend",
        policy =>
        {
            policy.WithOrigins("http://localhost:3000")
                  .AllowAnyHeader()
                  .AllowAnyMethod();
        });
});

builder.Services.AddControllers();

var app = builder.Build();
